column168: On 6/1/2012 Seattle stores clerk Mr. Plummer notified via email Richard Vernholm  mainteance operation supervisor for Horizon Air, that he just received a package containing dangerous good. Richard then contacted Bill Fourier Horizon Air FAA liaison and also contacted Jeff Brinlee acting Materials manager. Jeff and Richard contacted Mike Tobin Alaska DG manager at which time Mike released s self disclosure to the FAA. The Portland stores clerk was completing maintenance station restocks and had this package mixed with all other items to be sent to Seattle. The clerk was called away to drive an AOG part to the terminal and when returned boxed everything up and shipped it to Seattle. The package did not fail.

column168: Landstar Ranger contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor to respond to an apparent tote puncture on a trailer at the pilot Truck Stop in Lugoff, SC. Apparently the driver was attempting to move a tote with a strap and the strap broke resulting in the tote puncture. The contractor responded, transferred the remaining material into a new tote. They then cleaned up the released material. They solidified the material in the trailer with absorbents. On June 2, 2012, they returned, unloaded the trailer, cleaned up the released material and containerized the waste for disposal. They then pressured washed the impacted parking lot clean and collected the rinseates for pending disposal.

column168: On June 6th, 2012 at 08:15 warehouse agent was in the process of breaking down an ULD.  Upon picking up one carton (CN 26) warehouse agent noticed that the box was wet from the bottom and isolated the box, then notified to Supervisor on duty.  All the other boxes were checked and found an additional three boxes wet from the bottom.  All four boxes were isolated and absorbent material was place on the bottom to reduce leakage.  Upon close inspection it was found that one inner jerrican from CN 26 had been punctured by sharp staple used to close the box bottom.  Other three boxes were wet damage from the exposure to the leakage from CN 26.  Total leakage is about 4 fluid onces.
column169: During investigation it was found the bottom side of the box was not protected by extra cardboard, the staple used to secure the bottom side was sticking up and puncture the metal jerrican. In case metal staples are used, it will be recommended to ensure to place layers of cardboard to protect the inner receptacles.

column168: A trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  While picking up a pallet of drums with the forklift, a drum fell from the pallet onto the trailer floor, cratering the drum, bending the lid and causing some material to fall onto the floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  Absorbent pads were used to clean up the material from the dock floor and also placed into the salvage container.  The shipment was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility and the trailer was placed out of service until such time it could be decontaminated.
column169: The forklift operator was instructed to slow down and use more caution when picking up pallets of drums that may be unstable.

column168: During a routine yard check, a rolloff box was found to be slowly dripping onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal equipment, and placed a suitable absorbent material onto the small puddle that had formed on the concrete containment area.  The abosrbent cleanup material was placed into the box.  A spray sealant was put onto the leaking area and the box was taken down the street to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The box was not leaking at time of pickup or while sitting in the ten day storage yard.  It is believed that the seal deteriorated while the box was sitting in the sun for a day.  The box was taken to the maintenance facility after being emptied for a new tailgate seal.

Upon completion of loading, the manhole cover was not completely closed.  When the cargo tank was moved, liquid splashed out of the loose manhole cover.  The material was released over a course of approximately 1 1/2 miles to 2 miles.  The driver stopped the vehicle and secured the loose manhole cover and cleaned all spilled material from the cargo tank.  Material that had spilled onto the roadway evaporated before a contractor could reach the scene.
column169: The driver involved in this incident has undergone specific cargo tank training with emphasis on manhole and valve closures many times in the past.  He simply did not follow standard operating procedures by not ensuring the manhole cover was fully tighened prior to moving the vehicle.  Operating procedures will be re-evaluated as well as current training procedures.

Pressure on the car was 170psi with 4" outage.  The large O-ring in the pressure relief device was found to be misaligned and pinched.  Two new O-rings and a new cap were installed which stopped the release.  SEAL 433366 was applied.

column168: UPS PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A WHITE ENVELOPE PACKAGE IN THE SMALL SORT THAT WAS "WARM TO TOUCH" AND NOTIFIED UPS DESIGNATED RESPONDER. UPON ARRIVAL TO PACKAGE, THE RESPONDER COULD SMELL "SCORCHED PACKAGING" AND NOTICED A SCORCH MARK APPEARING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE ENVELOPE PACKAGE. THE RESPONDER THEN DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT & BEGAN TO PROCESS THE SHIPMENT AS THE HEAT EVENT WITHIN THE ENVELOPE APPEARED TO BE FINISHED.  AT THAT TIME THE RESPONDER CUT OPEN THE ENVELOPE AND DISCOVERED 18 SMALL LITHIUM ION BATTERIES OF VARIOUS MAKES. TWELVE OF THE BATTERIES APPEARED UNDAMAGED, BUT SIX SHOWED SIGNS OF SCORCHING AND WERE FUSED TOGETHER IN TWO GROUPS OF THREE BATTERIES EACH. ONE BATTERY CASING SHOWED SIGNS OF SIGNIFICANT EXPANSION.

column168: On 6/03/2012, at 1210 hrs., personnel in the CSXT East Chicago yard discovered tank car PPRX 55020, a load of Pentanes, UN1265, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, WRB Refining, was notified. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was leaking from the magnetic gauging rod cover. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper,of Phillps 66 company. SWS installed a wooden plug to seal the leak until an OTMA could be obtained for movement of the car.   The incident did not require a special switching move. column62: Deterioration or Aging; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car PLMX 30182 was reported leaking product from the top manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no further product release was observed when PLMX 30182 remained motionless. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected PLMX 30182 and observed product staining around the base of the manway nozzle with all spillage evaporating.  All manway securement bolts were found tool tight and a manway gasket sealing problem was suspected as the leak cause. No suitable replacement manway gasket was readily available to the BNSF responder, so a response contractor was summoned to replace PLMX 30182's manway gasket. In the mid-afternoon of 6/06/2012, contract responders replaced the damaged manway gasket applied onto PLMX 30182 and resecured the manway closure. The removed manway gasket appeared compressed with some shredding noted around the gasket's inner circumference. Intact shipper seal numbered 0021262 was replaced by seal numbered 477342.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On May 16, 2012, one poly tote of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution was punctured by a piece of wood from a damaged pallet and released approximately 220 gallons of material onto the trailer floor and shoulder beneath the trailer. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to transfer the remaining material from the damaged tote into 3 55-gallon drums to be sent back to the shipper. The environmental contractor neutralized the released material and then applied granular absorbents. All of the impacted absorbents were collected and containerized for transportation and disposal. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release.

A rolloff box arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  The receiving person noticed liquid leaking from the rear door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and applied an absorbent material to the affected area.  The box was moved into containment and the sample was immediately sent for analysis to expedite processing at the intended waste disposal facility.  The absorbent material was swept up and put into the rolloff box and it then entered the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: While loading the box, too much material was on one side, making it unstable.  To move it over, the generator applied a water jet to the load.  This added too much water content to the solids.  The driver took the load next door to the intended waste disposal facility, unaware that the load would be dripping.  The driver was issued a warning letter for accepting and transporting the load in this condition.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car GATX 54178 with fresh product stains on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical responder immediately inspected GATX 54178 and reported the leak source was the manway closure.  All six manway securement bolts were not tool tight which prevented a good manway closure seal. The responder properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts. The shipper manway seal was intact and remained intact after the manway was secured. The responder wiped product spillage from GATX 54178's safety appliances. No ground impact from spillage was prevalent. No further product release at the manway closure was observed during subsequent movements of GATX 54178 in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Fill valve closed and the driver tried to blow the hose clear with the air off the truck causing the hose to over pressurize. He opened the bleeder valve to relieve the pressure but apparently didn't have it opened far enough to relieve all of the pressure or didn't let it bleed off long enough. When he tried to release the hose from the storage tank the pressure caused it to pop off and lose approximately 1 gallon into the customers containment area. The valves on the storage tank and the delivery vehicle were already closed so no more action was needed. Some also got on the driver but he was wearing all his propper PPE so had no injuries as a result. The driver and plant operator where able to water the spill down inside the containment area. Plant safety personel also responded but no reports were issued.
column169: Driver was required to review company SOP's (Safe Operating Procedures) on Aqua Ammonia Cargo Transport Deliveries. Also retrained by ASP management on correct unhooking procedures.

column168: EVENT # 33848                                                                                                       SPILL - LOADED, D/R N/A, 1/2 GAL HAZ.  ID ARRIVED AT SHIPPER TO PICK UP PRELOADED TRLR, DIDN'T FIND ANY PROBLEMS DURING PRE-TRIP ... ONCE HE PULLED OFF CUST SCALE HE NOTICED PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED OUT OF AIR INTAKE TUBE.  CUST CLEANED W/PADS.  ID DID SLOSH TEST AND STILL LEAK.  CUSTOMER THEN CHECKED DOME LID AND IT WAS LOOSE.  THIS WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK, NOT THE TUBE.  APPROX. 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT RELEASED.

Per MSDS package contained undeclared regulated UN3272. The lid came off the bottle causing the spill of approximately 450ml. The package also contains five metal cans which do not have positive closure yet did not spill. Talked with Gary Mohr of the FAA at 1403CST and will forward 5800, MSDS, and contact information via email. AFW hub is holding package for FAA.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: STERICYCLE DRIVER PICKED UP THE TRAILER COMBINING THE WASTE ON 6/6/2012 AND PROCEEDED TO DELIVER IT TO OUR SALT LAKE CITY PLANT FOR PROCESSING . THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT A SCALE AT MILE MARKER 4 ON EAST BOUND I-80 JUST WEST OF RENO, NV. WHERE BEING INSPECTED BY THE NEVADA HIGHWAY PARTOL, THEY NOTICTED BLOOD LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER DOOR'S. AT THIS POINT WE STARTED OUR REPORTING PROCEDURES AND CALLED OUR CONTRACTED CLEAN-UP COMPANY TO FIND, CORRECT, AND CLEAN-UP THIS PROBLEM. THEY FOUND 2-90 GAL CONTAINERS THAT WERE LEAKING BLOOD ABOUT HALFWAY IN THE TRAILER. THE CRACKS WERE ABOUT 10 INCHES OR SO LONG IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINERS. THE CONTAINERS WERE REPACKAGED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. THE CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING FOR UP TO 9 HOURS AND 30 MINUTES MAX BEFORE THE PROBLEM WAS CAUGHT AND CORRECTED.

column168: Shipper tendered container, SELB463349-1/WB2972113, as hazardous on 6/8/2012 in Tacoma for loading to Horizon Kodiak, KO845N, for transit to Anchorage. Shipment was loaded and ship sailed. After vessel's arrival and during a random inspection it was discovered that shipper had failed to declare the UN1090/3. All pertinent parties were notifiied and corrective action taken.
column169: Shipper must monitor loading closely to ensure all hazardous commodities are capture and their declaration is correct, prior to tendering to the trucker and ocean carrier.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility and was observed to have a leak.  It was placed into containment.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking drum was identified and placed into a suitable salvage container.  The material leaking contained PCBs.  The liquid was contained with absorbent pads.  The stained pallets, and all spill cleanup materials were placed into suitable salvage containers.  The trailer was taken to a cleaning and repair facility to clean and replace any contaminated areas.  Tennessee Emergency Management Agency was called and assigned incident number 1228.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: Although no signs of nails or sharp objects were found, the bottom of the drum appeard to have a puncture hole.  The drum was not leaking when picked up or loaded at the origin facility.  All involved personnel have been talked to regarding the importance of checking drums, trailers and pallets for hazards.

column168: During a routine pretrip inspection, the driver noticed a small leak from the rear door of the rolloff container.  After placing absorbent pads under the drip, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the affected area.  The door was closed tighter and a spray on foam material was put on and around the leaking area.  The truck then left and stopped at the Clean Harbors Cincinnati facility where the leak was deemed to have been stopped.  The load then continued to the intended waste disposal facility.  Ohio EPA was notified and assigned incident number 1206-24-1466.
column169: The rear door to the rolloff box was not properly closed.  After tightening it and placing the foam sealant over the area that had leaked, the load continued without further incident.

column168: A rolloff box was being offloaded at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility when liquid sloshed over the top of the back door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and shoveled up the affected gravel and soil and placed them back into the box.  The material contained benzene.  The NRC was notified--incident number 1015058.  The TCEQ was notified--incident number 20122007.
column169: The generator was notified that there was too much liquid in the material.  They advised that they would check their process to insure that it was properly dried before loading.

HE YELLED "FIRE" AND SUPERVISOR BEN MOGAB CLEARED THE AREA, AND LINDSEY GRABBED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND TRIED TO OUT OUT FIRE WHICH IMMEDIATELY RE-IGNITED. AT 8:35PM THE EVACUATION ALARM SOUNDED AND RANDY LIMBAUGH OF THE PE DEPARTMENT SENT LINDSEY OUT OF THE BUILDING, SECURED THE AREA, AND CONITNUED TO CONTAIN, AND TRY TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT 8:50PM AND WERE ABLE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITH 2 1/2 EXTINGUISHED AND PRESSURIZED WATER FROM THEIR HAND HELD CONTAINERS. THE BUILDING WAS RELEASED AT 9:40PM AT WHICH TIME THREE UPS DESIGNATED RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL CONTENTS AND BELTS. ALL ARRIVED IN PROPER PPE, USED DECISION TREE'S AND PH TAPE, AND CLEANED THE SPILLED CONTENTS AS WELL AT THE DEBRIS FROM THE BELTS AND FLOORS. THE AREA WAS RELEASED FROM THE UPS RESPONDERS AT 10:05PM, AND ALL DAMAGES WERE RETURNED TO THE DMP PROCESSING FOR PROCESSING.THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS A STATIC DISCHARGE.

column168: Superior Carriers contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor to investigate and begin cleanup operations from an apparent loose washout cap on a tanker. The contractor indicated that the washout cap was lost in transit, They applied absorbents to the impacted area of pavement and wiped the side of the trailer clean. It appears that the release happened 10 miles earlier at the on ramp as the cap was found and the first spill was also cleaned up earlier in the day by our contractor. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal. The tanker was released and it returned to the terminal to wash off the setup residual resin on the exterior of the tanker.

Central Transport contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor to cleanup a release from a tote that apparently was impacted during the unloading process at the terminal. The contractor transferred the remaining material into a new tote. They then neutralized the released material, applied absorbents to the impacted areas, worked them in and swept the impacted areas clean. All waste was containerized and left on site for pending disposal.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, Bulk Transportation Co. driver was involved in a vehicle accident, which caused truck to rollover.  Mississippi State Police and Hattiesburg Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Bulk Transportation Co. dispatched a rescue tanker to recover the product from the overturned tank truck.  United States Environmental Services was contacted to perform cleanup and assist in recovery efforts.  Product was transferred from overturned truck to rescue tanker without further incident.  Approximately 2 gallons of product were released from the dome cover during transfer.  Approximately 5 gallons of vehicular fluids were also released from the tractor as a result of the overturn.  Vehicular fluids affected the roadside soils.  Per authorization from Mississippi DEQ representative on site, USES utilized Oil Gator on the impacted soils, which was worked in to serve as a bioremediation process.  There was no threat or impact to state waters.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: Bulk Transportation Co. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On 06/15/2012, at 1847 hrs., CSXT personnel in Queensgate Rail Yard, Cincinnati OH, discovered UTLX 500159, a loaded tank car of Toluene, leaking liquid from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the car shop, away from CSXT employees, awaiting a transfer due to a defective liquid line valve. The shipper, Marathon Petroleum Company, was notified through shipper contact number 877-627-5463. A CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS Environmental, was dispatched to respond to the scene and found the liquid valve, where it is attached to the liquid line pipe, was leaking. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper representative, Roger Spring, 606 921 6255. SWS secured the leak by removing the valve, cleaning the threads, placing pipe tape on threads and replacing the valve. The leak was secured and the car was held for transfer into another rail car and return of rail car once empty to the Marathon Plant for repairs This incident did NOT require a special switch move.     A 7.1 has been filed.    NARRI cause code: 282     NARRI Formula: 5 ( 5 + 3 ) ( 2 + 0 ) = 80

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car ECUX 371018 was reported dripping residue product from the bottom outlet during normal switching operation in the railyard. No product release was observed when ECUX 371018 remained motionless and leaked liquid evaporated. Contract responders inspected ECUX 371018 finding the bottom operated bottom outlet valve's (BOV) operating handle not secured in the closed position. The operating handle appeared modified at the handle pin seating area and would not hold in the closed position. The BOV operating handle was moved to the closed position and wired securely to keep it stationary. The leak source was at the BOV closure cap which was not tool tight. With the BOV in the closed position, the bottom outlet cap (BOC) was removed to inspect the BOC gasket and check for further residue product drips. The BOC gasket appeared serviceable and no liquid was observed at the BOV outlet with the BOV closed. The BOC was reapplied and properly tool tightened. Intact seal ExxonMobil 0219275 was replaced with seal numbered 116628.  ECUX 371018 was redirected to a repair facility for furtherance.

CONDUCTOR WALKED TRAIN ENCOUNTERED A CHEMICAL SMELL, THE CONDUCTOR MOVED UP-WIND NOTIFIED AMERICAN RAILROAD DISPATCHING CENTER (ARDC), ARDC MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO ALL CONCERNED.    (A)PACKAGE FAILURE: TANK CAR UTLX 202722 RUPTURED A 30 INCH DIAMETER HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. THIS RUPTURE WAS CAUSED BY THE COUPLER ASSEMBLY ON TANK CAR NATX 310210 STRIKING THE UNDERNEATH SIDE OF CAR UTLX 202722. (B)PACKAGE FAILURE:  TANK CAR NATX 310213 RUPTURED A 30 INCH DIAMETER HOLE ON THE UPPER END CAP OF THE CAR.  THIS RUPTURE WAS CAUSED BY THE COUPLER ASSEMBLY ON TANK CAR SHPX 210316 STRIKING THE UPPER END CAP OF CAR NATX 310213.      DURATION OF RELEASE:  ONE HOUR.    MITIGATION: ISRR WORKED WITH STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES IN CONJUNCTION WITH OUR CONTRACTORS TO HAVE THE MOST EFFECTIVE MITIGATION PROCESS TO RESOLVE THIS INCIDENT.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 AM, JUNE 24, 2012, A CARDINAL NUCLEAR PHARMACY SERVICES VEHCILE LOST CONTROL WHILE TURNING FROM NOB HILL ROAD ONTO STATE ROAD 84 WEST IN DAVIE, FL. THE VEHICLE LOST CONTROL DUE TO SLICK CONDITIONS AND ROLLED ONTO THE DRIVER'S SIDE. THE VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT WAS A FORD RANGER CARRYING CLASS 7 RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL USED FOR READIOPHARMACEUTICALS. THE FIRST RESPONDERS AND FIRE DEPARTMENT REMOVED THE DRIVER FROM THE VEHICLE BY REMOVING THE WINDSHILED.  THE VEHICLE WAS TURNED BACK ONTO ITS WHEELS, AFTER EXTRACTING THE DRIVER. WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS BEING TURNED OVER, THE TRUCK BED COVER WAS TORN OFF THE VEHCILE. THIS CAUSED THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PACKAGES IN THE BACK OF THE BEHICLE TO BE EJECTED FROM THEIR BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE VEHICLE CONTAINED A TOTAL OF EIGHT (8) PACKAGES, SIX (6) LIMITED QUANTITY PACKAGES AND TWO (2) WHITE 1 PACKAGES. THE WHITE 1 LABELED PACKAGES CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 698 MCI OF TC-99M IN LIQUID FORM. ONE OF THE EJECTED PACKAGES BROKE OPEN AND A TUNGSTEN CONTAINER, KNOWN AS A PIG, OF LIMITED QUANTITY MATERIAL FELL OUT. THE TUNGSTEN CONTAINER WAS INTACT AND THE VISUAL INDICATION WAS THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL. A CARDINAL HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO CHECK FOR SUSPECTED CONTAMINATION. CONTAMINATION WIPES AND SURVEYS WERE TAKEN OF THE VEHICLE, PACKAGES, AND ACCIDENT SCENE. ALL READINGS INDICATED NO CONTAMINATION. THE PACKAGES WERE TAKEN BACK TO THE FACILITY BY THE CARDINAL HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE AND THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL AND WAS RELEASED LATER THAT DAY.
column169: THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WILL UNDERGO CORRECTIVE/PREVENTATIVE DRIVER TRAINING. IN ADDITION, THE DELIVERY CASE PACKAGE THAT FAILED, ALLOWING THE TUNGSTEN PIG TO FALL OUT, WILL BE INVESTIGATED. ALSO, THE CARDINAL HEALTH NUCLEAR PHARMACY SERVICES LOCATION WILL UNDERGO A POST-INCIDENT REVIEW/CRITIQUE TO IDENTIFY GOOD PRACTICS AND WHAT COULD BE IMPROVED WITH ANY SIMILAR INCIDENT.

column42: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column168: The driver of the tanker notices liquid on the top of the tanker, this being Hydrofluoric Acid he immediately moved the truck to an isolated area of the rest area.  A pvt. hazardous material response team along with the local fire, police and Indiana Department of Emergency Management were notified of the incident.    The product was transloaded into another tanker without incident.  The general area around the truck was evacuated (mostly other tractor-trailers) and all safety precautions was followed during the transfer.    It was determined by shop personal that the inside liner was attached by the 30% hydrofluoric acid.  A bulge beneath the lining was noticed and it was determined that the acid penetrated the lining and attached the steel outer casing.     The liner had been provisionally repaired in March in the same general area, it appease although the acid penetrated the seams of the repair.

An inbound intermodal trailer (FXFZ 973266) with LTL/mixed freight shipment arriving on a BNSF train was reporting leaking. FXFZ 973266 was carefully removed from its rail flatcar that it was riding atop and moved to the intermodal facility's containment area. Contract responders inspecting the interior of FXFZ 973266 found six 5 gallon poly drums of liquid detergents leaking, of which three drums were labeled as 'Corrosive' hazardous material. Responders reported the leaking poly drums buckled under the heavy lading stacked atop them. All leaking drums were placed inside two 55 gallon disposal drums for later disposal. The spillage inside of FXFZ 973266 was cleaned using a granular absorbent (Multi-Zorb) and absorbent pads. The spillage on the rail flatcar that FXFZ 973266 was riding upon was neutralized with an application of soda ash.

column168: A Newsom Trucking Driver arrived at Intercon in St. Louis to make a delivery of 4600 gallons of Hypochlorite Solution.  The driver spoke to an Intercon chemical operator upon arrival and proceeded to hook up to the connection indicated by the chemical operator.  A sample was taken from the trailer and the driver waited approximately 45 minutes for the product to be approved for unloading.  The chemical operator told the driver the product was approved, connected properly and he was good to unload.  The driver started unloading.  The tank the product is unloaded into is located inside a building with the connection to the trailer outside where the driver was unloading.  The driver was not able to view the tank or inside valves from the unloading area.  The chemical operator went into the building during unloading.  Approximately 15 minutes after starting the unload process, the chemical operator came outside and told the driver to shut down the unloading, in which he did immediately.  The driver was then told that the chemical operator had failed to shut off an inside valve before having the driver unload.  This valve is normally used by Intercon to unload product from the tank and is not visible from the truck unloading area. Approximately 900 gallons was released out of the tank valve onto the floor of the building.        The chemical operator closed the valve on the tank and had the driver continue unloading the product.  The tank had 3700 gallons of the 4600 gallons when the unloading was completed.  This report is being completed by Newsom Trucking to report an unintentional release during unloading.  No delivery equipment failed during this incident.  The failure was caused by Intercon chemical operator error by leaving the valve on the Intercon tank open during the unloading process.
column169: The driver followed Newsom Trucking procedures.  He verified with the Intercon chemical operator before unloading that he was connected to the correct line and got approval before starting the unloading process.  He stayed within 15 feet of the trailer and was able to shut down the unload immediately.   He reported the incident to his supervisor as soon as possible.  The driver will continue to work with the chemical operators to try to prevent this type of incident by asking questions before unloading and verifying connection to the correct piping.

column168: LANGER TRANSPORT SPILLED LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PROPIONIC ACID AT A CUSTOMER IN MEMPHIS, TN.    THIS SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE OF DRIVER ERROR. WHEN OUR DRIVER COMPLETED OFF-LOADING HIS TRAILER HE FAILED TO RELIEVE ALL OF THE PRESSURE OUT OF THE VESSEL. AS HE WENT TO SECURE THE CENTER END CAP ON THE DISCHARGE LINE HE ENCOUNTERED A PROBLEM. THE LINE HAD PRESSURE IN IT AND WHEN THE DRIVER SECURED THE END CAP IT CAME LOOSE CAUSING A SMALL SPILL. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE CUSTOMER CLEANED UP THE SPILL BY HOSING THE AREA UP WITH WATER AND SPEEDY DRY.

THE DRIVER WAS THEN RE-TRAINED ON HOW TO RELIEVE PRESSURE IN A TRAILER AND THE DISCHARGE LINES. WE HAVE SENT OUT A MEMO TO OUR DRIVERS ALERTING THEM ABOUT THIS INCIDENT AND WE WILL DISCUSS IT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column162: HAZ MAT PKG & TRANSPORT SUBJECT MATTER EXPERT
column168: Pacific Northwest National Laboratory (PNNL) recently received a package 2nd Day Air via FedEx from Sigma Aldrich (Allentown, PA).  Following receipt, the package was placed in a flammable material cabinet pending deliver to the final location (Sigma V Building).  The Teamster who transported the material to Sigma V reported odors in the flammable cabinet but no evidence of leakage in the cabinet or from the package.  Closer examination of the outer box noted dried stains and smeared ink that could have been related to a solvent leak.    The package was opened on June 14, 2012 in a fume hood at Sigma V.  Within the box was a plastic bag containing a single, small absorbent pad and a shrink-wrapped box.   The inner box was not damaged and the shrink wrap was intact; however, there was evidence of staining on the box inside the shrink wrap; within the inner box, the internal dividers were all damaged.  The inner box contained four 25-ml bottles of triethylamine.  The tamper-evident lids on the bottles were all intact.  Two of the four bottles were completely empty and one other bottle was half empty.  There was evidence that the red dye from the bottle lid had leached and stained the inner components of the inner box.  There was no wetness on any package components.   There was no evidence that the absorbent pad had absorbed any material.  There was no evidence of cracks or damage to the bottles or lids.    The bottles were identified as a Product of Belgium with a specific lot number.      Sigma Aldrich was contacted and they sent a replacement package overnight.  The second outer package had no evidence of damage but there were stains similar to the first.  The configuration within the outer package was similar to the first although there were two absorbent pads and additional paper to minimize movement within the outer package.  The inner box was again undamaged with intact shrink wrap but there was evidence of staining on the box.  Within the inner box, there was again evidence of damage to the inner components of the box.  The tamper-indicating lids were all intact and there were no cracks in the bottle or lids.   There was no wetness.  Three of the four 25-ml bottles in the second shipment were empty.  There was no evidence that the absorbent pads had absorbed any material.  The lot number on the second four bottles was the same as on the first four bottles.    In neither case was there a leak to clean.    There is no evidence to indicate at what stage the damage occurred – it may have occurred before it was received by Sigma Aldrich.  FedEx is listed as the carrier in this report, but it is not known that leakage occurred during their transport.  It is not known who transported the material from the country of origin.    Sigma Aldrich has asked that we return the two shipments so they can look into it further.
column169: Unknown cause.  The first outer package was damaged, likely en route from Sigma Aldrich, but it seems unlikely that caused the leak.  No specific recommendations at this time.

column168: Tank car CBTX 740004 was reported leaking product from its top fitting area in the railyard. Spillage on CBTX 740004's side shell was migrating downward and dripping onto the ground. BNSF mechanical personnel wiped the spillage off the side shell with absorbent pads and a contractor remediated ground spillage by collecting impacted ballast/soil followed by an application of Micro-Blaze microbial solution. Absorbent padding was placed inside the valve housing area to absorb any additional leakage. CBTX 740004 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area (pit). Contract responders inspecting CBTX 740004 reported finding the liquid valve  (4 inch flanged Jamesbury  ball valve) installed incorrectly (inverted) which allowed product to escape via the mounting flange (fitting plate) connection area as the studs nuts could not be fully tool tightened when valve was in the inverted position. The responders removed the liquid valve and correctly installed it by 1300 hrs. CDT on 6/08/2012.  Afterwards, a nitrogen leak test with internal pressure up to 30 psi was conducted and no further product leakage was observed. CBTX 740004 was power washed and all liquid collected in the containment pit was earmarked for appropriate disposal.  On 6/25/2012, Movement Approval FRA-12060517 received to continue transportation to consignee for unloading.

column168: Union Railroad train crew was transporting UTLX 650883 from Koppers facility within USS Clairton Works. Once the tank was weighed, the crew intended to take it to interchange with Norfolk Southern on #1 Connelly track. After going over the B-Yard scale, a crew member noticed steam coming from the end tank and reported the incident. It was determined that a heater coil (thermo-coupler) at the end of the tank had failed and elevated temperature material was leaking. Weight of the tank at the time it went over the scale was 170400 lbs and 117600 when it returned to Koppers. Material quickly solidified once cooled. Dikes were created to contain spill and once material cooled enough the flow stopped. Weavertown Environmental Group was contracted to remediate the spill and dispose of material.
column169: The failure of this tank's thermo coupler did not occur until the tank car was in transit. Union Railroad employees responded accordingly once the incident was discovered. Union Railroad recommends that shipper will continue to complete and document inspection of tanks released to the carrier to aid in the prevention of future incidents.

column169: Hoses are tested as required and occasionally develop small holes.  The load delivered prior to the leak was done with no release.  The driver could not have known a hole would develop on the next delivery.

column168: At 12:41 PM CST a Carman at the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Beaumont subdivision of the Port Arthur station noticed a heavy smell of ammonia emanating from car TILX 303855. KCS emergency services were notified and a response team was initiated.    At 3:00 PM Hazmat responders arrived on site to check the car for cause of leak. Upon visual inspection of the car, it was determined that the pressure plate of the car was not completely sealed; identified by approximately 3 bolts loose on the pressure plate apparatus. Responders were successful in tightening the pressure plate with pneumatic wrench 1/10 - 1/4 turn during a full tightening process. Snoop Solution was used to verify no more leaks had occurred.     File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.     *No injuries reported.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Driver loaded at a location around Miami, Tx and was headed to Binger, Ok to unload. The driver was eastbound on I40, near Weatherford, Ok, at mile marker 80, when his unit drifted to the shoulder. When on the shoulder, the driver stayed there for about 120 feet and tried to pull back onto the highway. The driver turned his steering wheel to the left and when the unit re-entered the highway, the product surge in the tank caused his tank to move to the left. The driver tried to correct this action, but could not stop the movement of the trailer. The trailer continued to move to the left, towards the center medium and overturned, in the center medium. The truck and trailer rolled over onto the drivers side of the vehicle. The driver was able to evacuate the truck and begin calling 911. The Oklahoma Highway patrol arrived on the scene. The Weatherford Fire department responeded to the scene. Foam was put down around truck and trailer. Driver notified his supervisor. The driver noticed that the tank was leaking condensate, UN3295, and began building a dirt dike to contain the product. The Highway Patrol at that time notified Environmental Cleanup Inc., out of Oklahoma City,Ok to repond to the incident. The product leaked for about 1 to 2 hours, before the flow of product was stopped. When the tank overturned, the contact with the ground and the metal poles in the center medium, punctured the side of the trailer and product began to leak out. Dikes and bouy's were used to contain the product. Also another trailer, with a pump, was moved to location to vacuum up as much product as possible, while it was leaking. The hole on the trailer was about half way down the trailer on the left side.
column169: Our company does yearly defensive driver training, but will ensure that re-entering the highway from the shoulder, will be emphazied. Procedures for proper re-entry to highway, such as slowing down unit to a minimum speed, use of slow smooth movements, etc will be taught to drivers.

column168: On June 29, 2012, an Landstar Inway tractor trailer experienced a load shift from an apparent windstorm that blew the trailer over which resulted in three 55-gallon drums of UN1993 drums being punctured. The incident resulted in the release of approximately 25 gallons of material inside the trailer and to the ground below. ERTS dispatched Environmental Management Specialists to the site where they performed the necessary cleanup. All waste was collected and containerized for proper disposal.

THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN ONTO WEST PERIMETER ROAD FROM A SIDE ACCESS ROADWAY. WHILE MAKING THE TURN, THE DRIVER HAD TO CROSS OVER A SET OF RAILROAD TRACKS. DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE TURN, THE DRIVER STATES HE WAS UNABLE TO SEE THE ONCOMING TRAIN AND WAS STRUCK. THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ONTO ITS SIDE. THE TRAILER WAS RUPTURED, BUT GIVEN THE LOW SPEED IMPACT AND THE WAY THE TRAILER FELL, ONLY A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF JET FUEL WAS SPILLED. NRC ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION.
column169: KAG WEST, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: Driver reported that the shipper loaded the cargo tank and secured the dome.  The driver was not allowed on top of the cargo tank at that facility.  driver drove about 5 miles to a safe area and inspected the top of the trailer. Dog ears on dome were tight and there was no indication of any leakage.  When driver arrived at the consignee about 80 miles away, there was some product in the crash box and dripping down the drain tube.  In looking back on the roadway, there was a 1' by 150' trail from a rough area on the road.  When the dome on the cargo tank was opened, it was noted that the dome gasket was missing.  It was later found inside the cargo tank by the tankwash.  it appears it may have fallen in when the trailer was jarred on the roadway.  There was no indication of leakage before that.  We called out an enviromental firm to clean up the roadway.
column169: Having the dome gasket fall into the cargo tank during transit is not a common occurence.  Not sure if it was not positioned properly or what may have caused the problem.  Proper inspection when closing the dome should be followed at all times.

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, tank car GATX 19707 was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell that emanated from the manway closure area. GATX 19707 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Contract responders inspected GATX 19707 finding the manway shipper seal intact and the manway securement bolts tool tight. Further inspection of the manway securement revealed that the manway gasket applied appeared damaged/compressed and was not sealing properly. The manway gasket was replaced and the manway lid properly resecured by Noon CDT, 6/27/2012. Spillage on the side shell evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was observed. Seal PSC 139223 was applied at the manway closure.

column168: ON JUNE 26, 2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 0800, THE TRAIN WAS IN THE NORTH YARD TRACK C07, HEADED SOUTH. CARMAN M ZARANTI WALKED THE TRAIN DURING WHICH, HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR, HE THEN GLIMPSED UNDER THE NEAREST RAIL CAR WHERE IT WAS THEN HE FOUND AN UNFAMILIAR BUILD UP; THAT RESEMBLED ICE. AT 0805 CARMAN M ZARANTI THEN POSITIONED HIMSELF UP WIND FROM THE RAILCAR, WHERE TRAINMASTER MICHAEL SPRESSER WAS THEN NOTIFIED. HE THEN NOTIFIED EVANSVILLE WESTERN RAILWAY'S VICE PRESIDENT AND GENERAL MANAGER, ROBERT BUCHANAN AT 0810. MR. BUCHANAN NOTIFIED THE DISPATCH AT 0815 AND THEN INSTRUCTED DISPATCH TO NOTIFY CHEMTREC. CARMAN M ZARANTI THEN REQUESTED SPRESSER'S PRESENCE AT THE NORTH YARD AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE NORTH YARD, CARMAN M ZARANTI POINTED OUT THAT THE LOADED TAEX 182 WAS LEAKING MOLTEN PHENOL FROM THE BOTTOM PLATE OF THE CAR. VICE PRESIDENT AND GENERAL MANAGER R BUCHANAN THEN NOTIFIED THE MATERIALS & LOGISTICS LEADER FROM SABIC INNOVATIVE PLASTICS (THE LAST KNOWN COMPANY TO LOAD THE CAR) JACK LOWERY. J LOWERY AND A TEAM OF SABIC EMPLOYEES THEN MEET US IN THE NORTH YARD WHERE THEY TIGHTENED THE ALLEN HEADS ON THE BOTTOM PLATE OF THE CAR AND CLEANED UP ALL CONTAMINATES THAT LEAKED FROM THE CAR. UPON EXAMINATION IT APPEARED TO ALL OF US THAT ONLY A PINT OF MOLTEN PHENOL ACTUALLY LEAKED FROM OF THE CAR. AFTER THE LEAK WAS REPAIRED, CLEAN UP WAS THEN PERFORMED, WE PLACED SUPERVISION ON THE CAR TO ENSURE THAT THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. AT 0925 THE AREA WAS THEN CLEARED AND IT WAS DETERMINED SAFE AND EVANSVILLE WESTERN RAILWAY COULD RESUME NORMAL OPERATION.

column168: 6/25/2012: At approximately 11:30AM, while performing a routine inspection at Norfolk Southern's West Falls Yard, Philadelphia/Lower Merion, PA, FRA Chief Inspector J. Moore noted an odor from tank car UTLX 647375, residue last contained Acetic Acid, glacial.  Further examination noted the bottom outlet nozzle threads were wet.  Mr. Moore notified the CR crew FP06 (MV5) who happened to be working in the yard at the time, who further notified the CR Stony Creek (Chester) yardmaster, who in turn notified CR Risk Manager A. Richter.    Hepaco-React was dispatched to the yard to inspect and remediate the problem.  NS Environmental Mgr. J. Casey, was also notified by CR's Richter.      Further inspection by Hepaco-React noted the 4" bottom outlet cap was not even hand tight.  With a pail under the outlet, the closure plug for the 2" bottom outlet auxiliary valve was removed and valve opened.  Approximately 1 pint of product drained into the pail.  Additionally noted pieces of gasket coming through the outlet opening as well.  Once the valve was drained, the 4" bottom outlet cap was removed, revealing a deteriorated bottom outlet valve closure cap gasket.    Gasket replaced with Teflon gasket, and cap reapplied and resecured tool tight with an adequate tool.  Bottom outlet auxiliary valve closed and closure plug for said valve reapplied, also to tool tightness.  No further seepage noted after observing the valve for a few minutes.  Car okayed to be shipped to original destination, BP Amoco, Texas City, TX.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: Incoming shipment from Entergy Waterford manifest number 565-12-1008 (T123020) during the unloading process was found to be leaking some liquid contents. The shipment was a Class 7 shipment shipped as UN2910 (limited quantity). The container was placed in a secure building to collect the leaking material. Surveys indicate no loose contamination above Department of Transportation limits, however there was a small amount visible resin on the trailer. Samples were collected and counted on a gamma spectroscopy.  The sample consisted of 450 ml of liquid with a very thin film layer of resin in the Sample container. The liquid sample was counted for two hours at EnergySolutions Bear Creek Lab. The results were Co-60 at 5.31E-8 µCi/ml, Cs-134 at 5.67E-8 µCi/ml, Cs-137 at 1.19E-7 µCi/ml. The shipment consisted of four 96 ft3 metal boxes inside a twenty foot  metal ISO container with a Type IP-1 rating for solid material only. The four internal boxes were supposed to have contained dewatered bead resin. However the boxes contained free standing liquid as well as the resin. During transport the boxes appeared to leak liquid solution containing water and resin. The solution then appeared to leak through the doors of the twenty foot cargo container onto the trailer.
column169: To prevent recurrence resin should be properly dewatered before loading into a Type IP-1 container that is rated for solid material only.

column168: 6/28/12: At approximately 7:30PM, CR crew FL35 was switching cars at Livernois (Detroit, MI) Yard into track #6 eastbound class.  ACFX 86692, load, Potassium Hydroxide Solution, had already been switched into track.  Tank car UTLX 642291 load Petroleum Lubricating Oil was switched into the track behind ACFX 86692 with apparent more force then necessary.  Hard coupling causing the spring loaded, reclosing style, 75 p.s.i. presure relief device to function as designed, with product released in an aerosol like condition.  CR crew FD62 sitting inside locomotive NS 5242, alongside ACFX 86692, on track 5 eastbound class waiting for clearance to move.  Track 6E and subject tank car on FD62 conductor's side of locomotive.  Windows open in the locomotive.    A fine mist of the released product contacted the FD62 conductor and conductor trainee through the open window of the locomotive.  FD62 Engineer on opposite side of the locomotive and was not effected.  Both the Conductor and Conductor trainee went into the yard office, washed up and gave statements to Trainmaster K. Johnson explaining what had occurred and advised they were not in need of any medical attention and went back to work.    CR Risk Manager A. Richter notified and contacted emergency response contractor EQ to respond.  EQ's Tom Wildman responded and met with CR Trainmaster J. Higgins.  Locomotive was inspected and decontaminated with a vinegar solution on the side that was contacted with the product.  Inside of locomotive was also wiped down with the same solution.    Tank car ACFX 86692 was inspected from end to end and all valves and fittings.  Small amount of product on top of car and sides.  Origination confirmed to be from the tank car's pressure relief device.  All areas effected by the PRD release were treated with the vinegar solution and car was okayed to be forwarded to original destination, PVS Chemical, Norwood Plant, Detroit, MI.  Customer notified by CR's A. Richter of the incident for their information.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: BNSF employees in the railyard reported tank car GATX 17681 emanating a strong product odor. GATX 17681 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection by hazardous material responders. The contract responders inspecting GATX 17681 reported finding the manway closure was the source of a product leak and reported odor. Three of six manway securement bolts were found not tool tight. The nozzle style manway gasket applied was not fitting properly which prevented a good closure seal. The responders replaced the nozzle gasket with a Gore-Tex rope gasket at the manway lid.  The manway was closed and properly secured. New seal 162638 was applied at the manway. Spillage around the manway nozzle was sprayed with a Micro-Blaze solution. No ground impact from spillage was observed.

column168: While unloading freight material handler discovered an IBC in the nose of the trailer that was slightly leaking from a crease in the side of it. The IBC was either hit hard by other freight that was staged in the trailer behind it or it was as a result from the driver slamming on his brakes causing the freight behind the IBC to hit and crush the protective cage around the IBC. When the protective cage was crushed and pushed in it caused a small crease in the plastic of the IBC resulting in a small hole which consequently contributed to the unintentional release. The hole was repaired in the IBC and the spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container.
column169: When loading freight into trailer material handlers need to make sure they do not slam the freight into freight that is already staged in the trailer. Also, driver's need to make sure that all freight is secured against relative motion during the course of transportation.

column168: AN EXPERIENCED CDL-X DRIVER OPERATING A COMPANY-OWNED, STRAIGHT TANK TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND AT APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH ON A RURAL SECTION OF TWO-LANE US HIGHWAY. THE HIGHWAY WAS STRAIGHT, DRIVER VISIABILITY WAS EXCELLENT, AND THE ROAD SURFACE WAS DRY AND IN RELATIVELY GOOD CONDITION. THE HIGHWAY'S SHOULDER WAS NARROW (8-10 INCHES WIDE, AND THE ADJACENT, GRASS COVERED RIGHT-OF-WAY SLOPED TO A DRAINAGE DITCH. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 P.M. JUST 6-MILES FROM THE END OF HIS RETURN TRIP, IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DRIVER BECAME INATTENTIVE TO HIS DRIVING DUTIES SUBSEQUENTLY CAUSING THE TRUCK TO DRIFT OFF THE WESTBOUND SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AND GO INTO THE ADJACENT DRAINAGE DITCH AND ROLLOVER ON-QUARTER OF A TURN.    9-1-CHEMTREC AND THE DRIVERS HOME TERMINAL WERE CONTACTED. FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED AT THE CRASH SCENE PROMPTLY. THE COMPANY'S SPILL RESPONSE PLAN WAS SET INTO MOTION, AND A QUALIFIED CONTRACTOR WAS MOBILIZED AND WENT TO THE CRASH SCENE TO PEFFORM SPILL CLEAN-UP, HANDLING, DISPOSAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION DUTIES. THE DRIVER'S HOME TERMIANL ASSISTED FIRST RESPONDERS. THE COMPANY'S INDEPENDENT CRASH INVESTIGATOR WAS ON THE SCENE THE FOLLOWING MORNING TO ASSIST THE COMPANY IN DETERMINING THE CRITICAL EVENT AND THE CONTRIBUTING FACTORS INVOLVED IN THE CRASH.    THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED FOR ABOUT 7 HOURS. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN FROM THE SCENE FOR MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE TRUCK INVOLVED IN THE CRASH WAS TOWED. NO OTHER PERSONS OR VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN THE CRASH. THERE WERE NO OTHER WITNESSES TO THE CRASH, EXCEPT FOR THE DRIVER. THE ROLLOVER IMPACT CAUSED A SMALL SPILL OF 70-LBS.OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
column169: AFTER CONSIDERABLE REVIEW OF THE FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS OF THIS INCIDENT, THE FOLLOWING ARE THE RECOMMENDATIONS:    1. AUSTIN IS IN THE PROCESS OF INSTALLING A NEW ELECTRONIC ON-BOARD RECORDING (EOBR) SYSTEM ON NOT ONLY ITS FLEET OF SPECIAL PERMIT MARKED COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLES, BUT ALSO ON OTHER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTING VEHICLES IN IN ITS FLEET. THE NEW SYSTEM IS EQUIPPED WITH ENHANCED CAPABILITIES FOR AUSTIN TO MONITOR AND IMPROVE DRIVER BEHAVIOR.    2. THE NATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED SMITH DRIVING SYSTEM IS A CORE DRIVING PROGRAM WITHIN AUSTIN. ITS IMPORTANCE FOR TRANSPORTATION SAFETY TO AUSTIN IS SUCH THAT THE COMPANY IS PLANNING TO SCHEDULE A MEETING WITH ITS INTERNAL SMITH SYSTEM INSTRUCTORS TO SOLICIT THEIR INPUTS ON HOW TO PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS, INCIDENTS AND ROLLOVERS OF SPECIAL PERMIT MARKED COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLES. AUSTIN PLANS TO HAVE A REPRESENTATIVE OF A TRUCKING CONSULTING FIRM, WHOM THE COMPANY HAS MET WITH RECENTLY, TAKE AN ACTIVE PART IN THIS MEETING.

column168: WHILE ATTEMPTING TO ENTER THE SERVICE STATION THAT HE WAS SCHEDULED TO MAKE A DELIVERY, OUR DRIVER SCRAPED THE SIDE OF HIS TANKER TRAILER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AGAINST A LIGHT POLE, CAUSING THE CRACKS IN THE UNLOADING MANIFOLDS OF COMPARMENTS 4 AND 5 OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER OBSERVED THE DAMGE AND SHUT THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVE AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED 911 AND HIS SUPERVISOR TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE INCIDENT. THE FAILURE WAS CAUSED BY THE DAMGE TO THE UNLOADING MANIFOLD OF COMPARTMENT 4 AND 5 LOCATED ON THE UNDER BELLY OF THE TANKER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE THE DRIVER SHUT THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVES TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL RELEASE VALVES, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND BLOCKED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM EXITING THE UNLOADING MANIFOLDS, SPRAYED FOAM TO PREVENT VAPORS FROM IGNITING, BLOCKED ALL STORM DRAINS AND ROADWAYS, AND A SECOND TANKER WAS PULLED ALONGSIDE THE DAMAGED TANKER AND THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER WAS PUMPTED INTO THE SECOND TANKER. A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO CALLED IN TO PUMP OUT THE ENTIRE PRODUCT THAT HAD COLLECTED ON THE GROUND.
column169: AFTER THIS INCIDENT WE ISSUED A SAFETY STAND DOWN TO REVUEW THIS INCIDENT WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS COMPANYWIDE STRESSING THE NEED TO BE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS AT ALL TIMES WHEN ENTERING SERVICE STATIONS AND WHAT TO DO IN CASE OF AN EMERGENCY. THE DRIVER INVOLVED ALSO RECEIVED REFRESHER TRAINING IN REGARDS TO ALL OF OUR POLICIES ON LOADING, UNLOADING AND ENTERING SERVICE STATIONS. AT THIS TIME WE DON'T HAVE ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVING THE TRANSPORATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS; WE FEEL THAT ALL OF THE SAFETY FEATURES THAT WERE ON THE TANKER WORKED AS DESIGNED.

column168: On 6/30/12 at 0840 hours, personnel in the CSXT Avon yard discovered UTLX 5000, a loaded tank car of liquefied petroleum gas, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, Targa Transport, was notified via CHEMTREC report #2012-06-30-00041. CSXT hazardous materials manager was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor valve to be in the open position and secondary closure plug to be less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper representative David Lindow 713-826-2685. The open vapor valve and loose plug were secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5 (4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90   Cause Code: 134

column168: On June 24, 2012 at 2000 hrs, Kirk Higbie, Director of Safety & Environmental for the Port Terminal Railroad Association, contacted M&M Protection and requested a response to their Manchester Yard for a leaking LPG rail car. Rail car UTLX 99505, was “hissing” from the pressure relief valve on top of the car. Upon arrival met with Kirk Higbie and M&M ER Specialist Jeff Melton. The rail car was found to still be releasing from the PRV. The area of tracks where the rail car was located was walked with a 5 gas Photo Ionization Detector, (PID) monitor, the 5-gas PID registered 20.9 on O-2, 8-LEL, 432 - PPM, 124 – CO and 0 – H2S. The Manchester rail yard was shut down and a representative from Georgia Gulf arrived on site. The representative from Georgia Gulf reset the PRV and the car stopped releasing. The outage was checked on the rail car, it was 16” of outage. Pressure was checked on the rail car and was at 180 PSI, within specifications.

column168: On June 28, 2012 M&M Protection, LLC received a call from Kirk Higbie, Director of  Safety & Environmental for Port Terminal Railroad Association, who requested that M&M respond to a leaking rail car of Methyl Methacrylate Monomer at the Pasadena Yard, 910 N. Witter, Pasadena, Texas 77506, on track number 8.M&M personnel responded to the Port Terminal Railroad Association Pasadena Yard after receiving a call from Higbie regarding the rail car that appears to be leaking from the top of the car. Railcar number DOWX 74275 was located Additional M&M personnel arrived on location and Higbie was advised and a check was made to insure that the track was locked out and secure prior to the commencement of work. M&M personnel mounted the car and opened the protective dome lid. Inspection revealed that there was product leaking out of the 4” liquid valve. It was also observed that the 4” cap and both 2” caps were loose and camlock ears not secured. Upon removing of the liquid cap it was observed that the O-ring normally located inside the cap was too small for the cap. It was also observed that product was seeping out from around the Dri-  Disconnect Check Valve assembly just downstream of the liquid ball valve. M&M Personnel replaced the O-ring inside the cap; the decision was made to wait for the crew from DOW to see if replacing the valve in the field would be beneficial. The decision was made to have the car returned to DOWfor additional repairs as long as the product does not leak from the cap. 09:45, verbal authority was given by the Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) to Port Terminal Railroad Association to transfer the rail car back to DOW for repairs. After receiving the authority to transport the car, the cap on top of the car was resealed and the protective dome was closed, resealed and prepared for transport.
column169: Dow/Rohm & Haas is investigating the cause of the check valve and ball valve failure to prevent future occurrence.

column168: Terminal Operator was impacted with DMAPA (flammable/corrosive liquid) while conducting rail car sampling. When processing the first car the operator opened the shell valve to relieve the stored pressure on the rail car and then proceeded to sample the rail car from the same valve. However, when the operator attempted to sample the second rail car, he did not utilize the shell vent valve, he utilized the eductor valve to vent the rail car and when doing so the pressure in the rail car forced the product stored in the line out of the rail can impacting the operator in the back , neck , shoulders and cheek. Once impacted the operator went to the safety shower to flush the product off his body. Failure on the part of the operator to wear the appropriate PPE and failure to follow procedures caused this injury.
column169: Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Future Recurrences are as follows:1) Review all procedures for accuracy and risk mitigations (through procedural development committee) and retrain all employees on the execution of each task (starting with rail car operations) 2) Review Plant Operating Orders (POO) for accuracy and update PPE requirements as a part of procedural review.

SUSPECTED UNDECLARED DG. DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST CONTACTED DG ADMIN TO ADVISE OF A SPILL OF GREEN LIQUID WITH CAUSTIC ODOR AND BUBBLING ON CONCRETE.  AGENT SUITED UP IN FULL HAZMAT GEAR AND CLEANED SPILL LOCALLY. AGENT   PERFORMED PH TEST WHICH TESTED POSITIVE FOR CORROSIVE PROPERTIES. OUTER PACKAGING WAS 1 FIBERBOARD BOX/SOAKED IN LIQUID. INNER RECEPTICLE WAS A "HOME DEPOT"-TYPE PLASTIC CONTAINER WITH IMPROPER SEAL. DUE TO COLOR AND ODOR AND POSITIVE CORROSIVE PROPERTIES WE SUSPECT MURIATIC ACID. SPILL CLEANED LOCALLY AND REMAINS OF SHIPMENT SECURED AND STORED IN SALVAGE DRUM CURRENTLY BEING HELD AT FEDEX VNY STATION LOCATION FOR FAA INSPECTION. NO INJURIES. NO OTHER PACKAGES AFFECTED.
column169: BOTH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE ARE NALCO HOLDING COMPANY.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE CONSIGNEE INFORMATION HAS BEEN PURPOSELY DUPLICATED AS THE SHIPPER, BY THE SHIPPER.  WE WERE ABLE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER 661-388-6755 WHO TURNS OUT TO BE MATT MCGILLICUDDY, FROM THEIR SANTA CLARITA, CA 91350 LOCATION.  ALSO INTERESTING TO NOTE THAT MATT TENDERED THIS BOX TO US IN ONE OF OUR DROP BOXES.  IF THIS HAD BEEN TENDERED TO A RECEIVING COUNTER, THE DUPLICATION OF SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE ON THE AIRWAY BILL WOULD HAVE BEEN QUESTIONED.  MATT ADVISED THAT THIS SHIPMENT WAS A LIQUID FROM A RINSE TANK FROM A METAL COMPANY.  MATT STATED HE WAS AWARE OF DG SHIPPING REGULATIONS BUT COULD NOT CONFIRM WHETHER OR NOT THIS LIQUID WAS DG.  I ALSO CONTACTED BRIAN BONDS 630-305-1000, THE SAFETY MANAGER AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION.  BOTH BRIAN AND MATT WERE ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE SPILL AND THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION UNDER SUSPICION OF UNDECLARED DG.

column168: The transloading operator at the TRANSFLO transloading terminal had just started transloading asphalt from a truck trailer to a railcar (GATX-47652) at 9:30 AM. The operator soon observed asphalt leaking on top of the railcar. The operator immediately shut the pump down to stop further leaking of asphalt. Approximately 1 gallon (US) was released from the loading connection on the top of the railcar and some spilled product ran down the sides of the railcar. The cause of the release was a deteriorated gasket in-between the product hose connection and the railcar fitting/adapter. The release material (asphalt) cooled down which caused it to solidify and then it was able to be scooped up by shovel and asphalt was placed in a 5-gallon waste disposal bucket.
column169: It was determined that a stronger type of gasket should be used for this transfer and that the terminal operator should ensure the gasket is replaced with a new gasket after every 3 railcars are loaded to reduce the chance that the gasket on the loading connection may fail again.

column168: A forty foot intermodal container GESU 643503 atop an intermodal rail flatcar was reported leaking by a BNSF switch crew that was scheduled to move rail cars into the dock facility for export via a marine vessel. GESU 643503 was cordoned off and equipment was ordered to lift GESU 643503 from its position on the intermodal flatcar. GESU 643503 was grounded trackside by 0200 hrs. PDT, 6/24/2012 for a response contractor to investigate leak source and remediate spillage. Responders reported one 55 gallon steel drum near the container nose section was found leaking, apparently from abrasion to an upper rolling hoop that rubbed against the exterior metal cage of an IBC tote adjacent to the damaged drum. Insufficient blocking and bracing allowed lading inside GESU 643503 to move. The damaged drum was placed into an overpack drum, labeled and secured. The inside of GESU 643503 was cleaned and all lading was returned inside GESU 643503. An intermodal container riding under GESU 643503 was also grounded trackside and exterior spillage on it was cleaned. The rail flatcar was also cleaned of any observed spillage. GESU 643503 remained grounded at its location awaiting drayage into the port facility.  On June 29, 2012, GESU 643503 was reported emanating an odor, possibly from residue spillage from GESU 643503, which resulted in a response from local emergency agencies. No additional hazardous material packages were reported leaking. The ground surface under GESU 643503 was cleaned of any observed residue product, as well as, the exterior bottom of GESU 643503 by another response contractor. GESU 643503 was then drayed off property to the response contractor's facility for additional decontamination and the transfer of lading into another suitable intermodal container.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process includes adherence to acceptable containerized loading patterns with appropriate blocking and bracing to eliminate longitudinal and lateral lading shifts.

column25: ENERGETIC MATERIALS RESEARCH AND TESTING CENTER (EMRTC)
column168: EMRTC (ENERGETIC MATERIALS & RESEARCH & TESTING CENTER), A PART OF NEW MEXICO TECH, IS A BAE SYSTEMS, MINNEAPOLIS, MN SUPPLIER. THEY WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKAGING, LABELING, AND ARRANGING THIS SHIPMENT OF INERT PRIMERS. JUNE 14, 2012 - EMRTC SENT BOX WITH INERT PRIMERS VIA FEDERAL EXPRESS (FEDEX) STANDARD OVERNIGHT SERVICE ON WAYBILL 8771 0247 9562 FROM THEIR LOCATION AT 1001 SOUTH ROAD, SOCORRO, NM TO BAE SYSTEMS, 4800 EAST RIVER ROAD, MINNEAPOLIS, MN. SHIPMENT WAS MADE IN A 4G UN RATED FIBERBOARD BOX - THE PACKAGING CONSTRUCTION AND TEST INFORMATON STAMPED ON THE BOTTOM WAS COVERED BY TAPE. JUNE 15, 2012 - BAE SYSTEMS, MINNEAPOLIS CLOSED FOR BUSINESS, SO BOX COULD NOT BE DELIVERED. JUNE 18, 2012 - FEDEX DELIVERED PACKAGE TO BAE SYSTEMS, WHO DELIVERED IT INTERNALLY TO THE RECIPIENT. NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR LABELING WAS ON THE BOX. JUNE 26, 2012 - BAE SYSTEMS EMPLOYEE OPENED THE BOX AND RAN DIAGNOSTICS ON THE PRIMERS. DURING THIS TASK, THE TESTING EQUIPMENT INDICATED ONE PRIMER WAS LIVE. THE EMPLOYEE TOOK APPROPRIATE ACTIONS TO NOTIFY INTERNAL BAE SYSTEMS PERSONNEL. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THE ERROR OCCURRED AT EMRTC. BAE SYSTEMS WAS UNAWARE THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED A LIVE PRIMER UNTIL IT WAS OPENED. BAE SYSTEMS APPROPRIATELY HANDLED THE SITUATION ONCE DISCOVERY WAS MADE.
column169: ENERGETIC MATERIALS RESEARCH AND TESTING CENTER (EMRTC) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED UPON DISCOVERY OF LIVE PRIMER. IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THIS SUPPLIER IS CONDUCTING AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION.

column168: The cargo tanker was loaded with sodium hypochlorite on Friday 06/22/12.  The tanker built up pressure over the weekend due to the extreme heat and on Monday 06/25/12 the driver failed to fully depressurize it before going on his deliveries.  When the driver arrived at his first delivery he made a sudden stop at the guard gate causing the wave motion in the tanker.  This motion along with the pressure build up caused the "pressure release valve" to open and 3 gallons of bleach or "sodium hypochlorite" to run down the side of the tanker.  The guard called the fire department, who in turn called Mississippi EPA.  We contacted SWS Enviromental to clean up the spilled sodium hypochlorite.
column169: Drivers will be retrained on the proper pre-trip inspections which include releasing the tanker pressure before leaving the plant.  Driver involved will be counseled for not following the pre-trip procedures

column168: 61 drums of RFL were being offloaded at Lufthansa Cargo ORD from a Towne Air Freight truck. One of the skids of RFL ( in plastic jerricans) was punchured by a metal protusion on the side of the truck. Two of the RFL plastic jerricans were punchured. This caused leakage as the skid was being taken off the truck into the Lufthansa Cargo warehouse. At that point the forklift driver stopped, secured the area, keep others away and called the manager. The manager segregated the area, and called a clean up company to recovery the material. The two drums were removed and will be disposed of by the clean up company ( legal landfill ) . The material if a flavoring used in foods, the packing group is III .
column169: Towne air freight was admonished to repair the truck. That is a metal protusion on the side of the truck will casue damage to other hazmat, liquid and non hazardouse cargo and the trailer should not have been used, especially to transport hazardous materials. Discussion with all involved, it was difficult for the forklift driver to avoid this, he had no warning and the hazardous material had been placed near the metal protusion so the forklift driver did not see this prior to offloading the skid. All agreed the forklift driver was not at fault, but that Towne Air Freight was at fault for operating this truck and not at a minimum blocking and marking the area until repair could be made.

column168: Tank car TEIX 112372 in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve area.  A BNSF mechanical responder applied sealant (Plug N Dike) around the threaded connection at the bottom outlet cap (BOC) that was wet with product. Afterwards, the product drips ebbed and TEIX 112372 was deemed safe to move to the facility's containment area/pit.  Contract hazardous material responders inspected TEIX 112372 at the containment area and removed the sealant around the BOC. The BOC was tool tightened approximately 1/4 turn and no further dripping was observed. The BOC gasket was not inspected. The BOC was wiped cleaned and monitored for an hour and no further drips noted. The intact shipper seal at the bottom outlet was not disturbed. The minor ground impact area at the initial railyard site was treated with a solution of Micro-Blaze.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Floor blocking material should have been in place to prevent movement during transportation. The inadequate B+B material caused the tote to be crushed resulting in a crack in the tote and to subsequently release the HZ material.

column168: Product was reported to be leaking from the bottom of the car. Upon tightening of all loose fittings, car was secured from further leakage.  Arrangements were made by the shipper to have OMI Solutions clean residual product on bottom outlet valve and neutralize spilled material.  On 6-26-12, cleaning and neutralization of released product had been completed and car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

column168: ON JUNE 29, 2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 0800, CARMEN MIKE ZARANTI PERFORMED A CLASS I BRAKE TEST ON A TRAIN IN MT. VERNON, IN YARD. THE TRAIN WAS IN THE NORTH YARD TRACK CO7, HEADED SOUTH. CARMAN M ZARANTI WALKED THE TRAIN DURING WHICH, HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR, HE THEN GLIMPSED UNDER THE NEAREST RAIL CAR WHERE IT WAS THEN HE FOUND WHAT APPEARED TO BE A WET SPOT ON A TIE UNDER THE CENTER OF THE CAR. AT 0810 CARMAN M ZARANTI THEN POSITIONED HIMSELF UP WIND FROM THE RAILCAR, WHERE TRAINMASTER SPRESSER WAS THEN NOTIFIED. HE THEN NOTIFIED THE MARTERIALS & LOGISTICS LEADER FROM SABIC INNOVATIVE PLASTICS (THE LAST KNOW COMPANY TO LOAD THE CAR) JACK LOWERY. HE THEN NOTIFIED THE TRAIN DISPATCHER AND INSTRUCTED THEM TO NOTIFY CHEMTREC. CARMAN M ZARANTI THEN REQUESTED HIS PRESENCE AT THE NORTH YARD AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE NORTH YARD, CARMAN M ZARANTI POINTED OUT THAT THE LOADED UTLX 641365 WAS LEAKING MOLTEN PHENOL FROM THE BOTTOM PLATE OF THE CAR. J LOWERY AND A TEAM OF SABIC EMPLOYEES THEN MEET US IN THE NORTH YARD WHERE THEY TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE BOTTOM PLATE OF THE CAR AND CLEANED UP ALL CONTAMINATES THAT LEAKED FROM THE CAR. UPON EXAMINATION IT APPEARED THAT ONLY A CUP OF MOLTEN PHENOL ACTUALLY LEAKED FROM THE CAR. AFTER THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED, CLEAN UP WAS THEN PERFORMED, THEY PLACED SUPERVISION ON THE CAR TO ENSURE THAT THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. AT 1000 THE AREA WAS THEN CLEARED AND IT WAS DETERMINED SAFE AND EVANSVILLE WESTERN RAILWAY COULD RESUME NORMAL OPERATION.

column168: Employee was pulling NH3 nurse tank westbound on oil road and tank started to fishtail. he attempted to recover but tank flipped over and when employees attempted to tip tank back over, valve failed causing release of all contents of tank.    Received a call regarding a rolled over 2 ton, single bottle nurse tank. Houston Farmers Coop-east of garretson, Rock County MN. Tank started fishtailing, rolled over in ditch. Cty Rd 7/201st St. which is located 6 miles east of Hardwick and 1.5 miles NW of Kenneth. Road is currently closed.    Tank is upside down in ditch and leaking from the SRV.  NRC has been notified, Law enforcement has notified MN Duty Officer. Advised that we should also make a MN Duty Officer notification.    Fire Dept is on Scene and applying water. Wind is ~5mph out of the NW. The town of Kenneth would be downwind. Advised that the fire department would have Incident Command of the scene and that we should coordinate with them.     The SRV may be damaged or just releasing pressure.  However since the tank is upside down it is likely that liquid is being released and the pressure will not be decreasing.  They are making an attempt to upright the tank.  Our personnel have APR protection. Advised that an APR may be insufficient protection. Advised that if there is a risk that the Fire Dept should complete hookups using SCBA protection.    Sounds like with the wind and water application that the risk of inhalation exposure would be minimal from the upwind direction.     Advised that photographs be taken of the incident and of any damage prior to and after repairs. Location has the ability to transfer product once the tank has been uprighted. Advised the MDA will likely be requesting a followup investigation and documentation submittal.     They will keep me advised of the response and request any additional resources if needed.    4:21 update: Notified that as the tank was being uprighted the SRV valve blew. Fire dept likely will not have enough water to control plume.  Will initiate evacuation in the downwind direction.  Advised that with a 1" hole the duration of the release will likely be short lived. No one injured. No one exposed. Advised that product may auto refrigerate and that once the tank warms vapors will be released if the hole is not plugged.     5:15 update: Tank is still leaking, Vapor valve was opened to relieve pressure. Fire department is in incident command all activities under their direction.  There is currently no evacuation being conducted.  The tank is a CHS owned tank with product being hauled out of our Magnolia location. NRC report number is 1013394.    7:27 update: Tank is upright and removed from the scene to a customers abandoned gravel pit.  Location is secure with fencing. Both the liquid and vapor valve assemblies sustained damage and still have the potential to actively leak.  The tank pressure is being taken away by bubbling in surface water at the gravel pit.  I requested that a water tank be used t
column169: Employees must recieve yearly training on working with NH3 and understand hazards of pulling trailers which have a moving product and have an extremely high center of gravity due to how high the nurse tank sits on the running gear. Employees need to adhere to the 25 mph towing speed to prevent incidents such as this from occuring.

column168: 1. ON 6/6/2012 AT 04:20 APPROXIMATELY 42,000 POUNDS OF HAN WAS TRANSFERRED FROM A TANK TRAILER TO THE STORAGE TANK. WHEN THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE, THE OPERATOR APPARENTLY DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THE TRAILER WHILE THE PUMP WAS RUNNING TO EMPTY THE HOSE AND TRANSFER LINES. THIS METHOD OF EMPTYING HOSES AND LINES IS NOT AN ACCEPTED PRACTICE NOR INCLUDED IN OUR OPERATING PROCEDURES. HE RELEASED THE TRAILER AND LEFT THE AREA WITHOUT CLOSING VALVES AND STOPPING THE PUMP. THE RUNNING PUMP PREVENTED THE OIL FROM BACKFLOWING FROM THE STORAGE TANK.    2. DURING A STORM EVENT AT 18:20 A SHORT ELECTRICAL POWER OUTAGE CAUSED THE PUMP TO STOP, ALLOWING THE OIL TO BACKFLOW FROM THE STORAGE TANK.    3. THE MAJORITY OF THE OIL FLOWED INTO AN ADJACENT CONSTRUCTION HOLE. A SMALL QUANTITY OF THE OIL WAS COLLECTED IN OUR STORMWATER SUMP.
column169: 1. OUR TANK TRUCK LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURE WILL BE REVIEWED WITH ALL OPERATORS. PROPER HOSE AND LINE CLEARING PROCEDURES WILL BE STRESSED.    2. THE OPERATOR RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS INCIDENT WILL BE DISCIPLINED.

column62: Human Error; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Employee was traveling on the dock with several cylinders on his forklift blades. When the employee came to a stop, one cylinder rolled off the blades, rolled 6 feet and gently struck an overhead door post. The collision caused gas to leak from the valve area. When the event occurred, I was no more than 20 feet away. I immediately located the placarding on the cylinder to make sure it was non-flammable at the very least. I saw the 2.2 green diamond marking on the cylinder and next walked quickly to the employee to verify the type of gas on the BOL. I verified the gas was carbon monoxide (not an imminent threat) and made sure no one was near or would come near the immediate area. I instructed the employee to stay away from the shipment that was leaking, and wait for my return. I then walked quickly to the office to place the call to the provided number on the BOL, while beginning to search the ERG. The associate on the phone instructed no imminent threat and told me it would be safe to move the shipment outdoors to finish leaking. I returned to the cylinder, and was able to verify that the valve had become slightly opened upon impact. After tightening the valve, the leaking stopped completely and I verified no further damage. I saw that the weight on the bill was 450 LBS. on 5 cylinders, and knowing that cylinders weigh 90 LBS when empty, I concluded that they were mostly empty, and that a negligible amount of gas vapor had probably evaporated. We up righted the cylinder, and I instructed the employee about proper movement of the cylinders on the dock. I then instructed that the shipment continue movement into our system.
