Driver was unloading the 2nd of 3 IBC's of Ferric Chloride to Grain Processing Corp, Washington, IN.  There is no dock at this customer location.  Therefore, the driver must position the IBC at the rear of the trailer so that the customer can remove with their fork-lift.  The driver moved the IBC to the rear of the trailer using an electric pallet jack. Driver failed to position the lift-gate as required to provide STOP barrier at the rear of the trailer.  The driver moved failed to properly judge the distance and the IBC was moved past the edge of the trailer floor.  The IBC then fell out of the trailer and onto the gravel parking lot below.  The poly IBC ruptured and cracked causing the entire contents to be released on the ground.  The contents were released in less than 10 minutes.  The release was immediately detected.  Grain Processing Corp personnel responded with in house resources and dike and contained the spill.  Lime was used to absorb the spill material.  Grain Processing setup proper disposal and of the spilled product and lime mixture through a contractor.       Note 1: The IBC was not available for inspection as Grain Processing took possession of the package.  This package is a rigid plastic IBC (UN31H1/Y) with structural equipment withstanding the stack load.  This IBC was manufactured by Snyder Industries.    Note 2: We were able to identify the IBC unit number assigned by Brenntag through our shipping paperwork.  Thus, we were able to track the last retest date of the container which was 03/05/2012.  We are unable to determine the manufacture date as we do not have possession of the IBC.  However, given the Brenntag unit number of 183900 that was assigned to this IBC we estimate the year of manufacture around Y2000 with an error of +/- 1 year.  We will update this report if more information becomes available.
column169: Retraining on proper unloading of IBC's from van trailers was conducted with all drivers at our Henderson, KY facility on 06/23/2012.  This also included retraining on proper use of electric pallet jacks and use of the trailer lift-gate as a backstop for IBC deliveries at facilities with no dock.

column168: DELIVERY VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTH ON CRD 151 WHEN RIGHT SIDE TIRES TRAVELED OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF ROADWAY. DRIVER OF VEHICLE ATTEMPTED TO RETURN THE VEHICLE TO THE ROADWAY BY TURNING THE STEERING WHEEL TO THE LEFT. THE RIGHT REAR DUAL WHEELS CAUGHT ON THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY, PUNCTURING ONE TIRE AND CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND SLIDE ACROSS THE ROAD INTO THE LEFT DITCH WHERE IT STRUCK A ROAD SIGN.    THE FUEL STORAGE TANK SUSTAINED A CRACK FROM THE SLICE AND RELEASED 200 GALLONS OF OFF-ROAD DIESEL FUEL ON TO THE ROADWAY AND DITCH WHERE THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST. 40 BAGS OF OIL DRY WERE BROUGHT TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH 4 BALES OF OIL BOOM AND 1 ROLL OF 30" X 150" ABSORBENT. OIL DRY WAS LAID DOWN AS A DAM (ON ROAD WAY AND EXTENDING INTO DITCH). OIL DRY WAS ALSO SPREAD TO COLLECT EXCESS FROM ROADWAY, TWO MORE DAMS WERE PLACED IN DITCH BELOW OIL DRY DAM. THESE DAMS WERE ABSORBENT MATERIALS WITH TARPS TO COLLECT ANY EXCESS BEYOND THE ORIGINAL DAM.    A BACKHOE WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND FUEL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND TAKEN TO SPRINGFIELD SANITARY LANDFILL, 2 LOADS OF 19.2 TONS AND 17.3 TONS WERE REMOVED. MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES SOLID WASTE MANAGEMENT PROGRAM WAS CONTACTED FOR SPECIAL WASTE DISPOSAL FOR THE CONTAMINATED SOIL PRIOR TO THE REMOVAL. MO DNR PERSONNEL WERE PRESENT AT THE SPILL SITE. ROCK AND SOIL WERE BROUGHT IN TO REPLACE MATERIAL REMOVED TO LANDFILL.

column168: PACIFIC TANK LINES DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON I-10 254' WEST OF 10 SBD 19.50 AT APPROXIMATELY 02:40. OTHER PARTY WHO WAS ALSO TRAVELING WEST ON THE I-10 LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE HITTING OUR VEHICLE IN THE LEFT FRONT STEER TIRE CAUSING OUR VEHICLE TO ROLL OVER ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE. WHEN OUR VEHICLE ROLLED OVER IT COMPROMISED THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK CAUSING A LOSS OF 7,269 GALLONS OF PRODUCT (GASOLINE/GASOHOL). OUR DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911 AND PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. POLICE AND FIRE WERE ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 03:10 AND PTL PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 03:25. PTL SAFETY MANAGER MADE CONTACT WITH OUR DRIVER AND ALL FIRST RESPONDERS. AT 03:45 PTL BEGAN TO ATTEMPT TO PUMP OUT THE REMAINING PRODUCT THAT WAS STILL ON THE VEHICLE. 04:20 PTL'S CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY ARRIVED ON SCENE TO BEGIN THE CLEAN UP OF SPILLED PRODUCT. 07:15 OUR VEHICLE WAS UPRIGHTED AND AT 07:35 THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE. THE CLEAN UP CONTINUED UNTIL 11:30 AND THE SCENE WA DECLARED SAFE AND CLEAN. IT WAS FOUND THAT THE OTHER PARTY INVOLVED WAS ARRESTED FOR DUI AND HIT AND RUN.
column169: AT THIS TIME PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. HAS NO SUGGESTIONS. PTL HAS A VERY EXTENSIVE DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM AND HAS NO CONTROL OF THE BAD JUDGMENTS OF OTHER ROAD USERS.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS DRIVING EASTBOUND ON ODANA RD. WHEN A RED CAR SWERVED IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK CAUSING OUR DRIVER TO BRAKE AGGRESSIVELY TO PREVENT A REAR END CRASH. THE BRAKING ACTION CAUSED A LIQUID SURGE IN THE TANK, AND THE MAN HOLE COVER ATOP THE TANK TO POP OFF. LESS THAN 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. PRODUCT DID NOT REACH THE STORM SEWER. A POLICE OFFICER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE IN LESS THAN 5 MINUTES. THE LICENSE PLATE OF THE DRIVE THAT CAUSED THE INCIDENT WAS NOT OBTAINED. ONCE HAZMAT RESPONDED A NEW TANK LID WAS SECURED TO THE TANK. HAZMAT PUT DOWN THREE BAGS OF OIL DRY TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT. A STREET SWEEPER CAME BY TO CLEAN UP THE OIL DRY. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR. NO CITATIONS WERE GIVEN. WE HAD TO PURCHASE THREE BAGS OF OIL DRY FOR THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.
column169: OUR COMPANY DISCUSSED THE INCIDENT WITH ALL OF OUR DELIVERY DRIVERS. WE DISCUSSED HOW WE COULD PREVENT A SIMILAR ACCIDENT. RESTATED THE IMPORTANCE OF DRIVER AWARENESS AT ALL TIMES AND DEFENSIVE DRIVING. WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED ADDITIONAL TANK INSPECTIONS, PRE-TRIP AND ON DELIVERY ROUTES. WE HAVE ALSO CONTACTED THE TANK MANUFACTURER TO GET ADVICE ON ADDITIONAL STEPS TO HELP SECURING THE LID TIGHTER. WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED THEIR RECOMMENDATIONS OF USING BOLTS, NUTS AND WASHERS TO SECURE THE LID TIGHTER, INSTEAD OF THE STANDARD SCREWS THAT COME WITH THE TANK.    IN CLOSING, WE UNDERSTAND THE RESPONSIBILITY OF TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SAFELY. WE TRY TO BE AS VIGILANT AS POSSIBLE. THIS WAS AN UNFORTUNATE ACCIDENT, AND I BELIEVE THAT OUR DRIVER HANDLED THE SITUATION TO THE BEST OF HIS ABILITY.

column168: Shipper (IDS Import and Export Batteries, Nassau, Bahamas) offered as shipment declared as 10 pallets of batteries. There was no hazardous description on the original bill of lading. Prior to final delivery the shipper provided a corrected IMO. US Customs identified the shipment for inspection when it had been off loaded at the Crowley terminal at Port Everglades. The shipment was transported to the US Customs warehouse on Macintosh Road within Port Everglades. Upon opening the container the US Customs officers noticed leakage and notified Crowley who arranged for there mediation of the shipment by Cliff Berry Environmental Services. There was no release outside of the container.The shipper's packaging was not compliant with 49 CFR §173.159. The batteries were used and were shipped to the consignee for recycling.
column169: The shipper was provided instructions as outlined in 49 CFR §173.159 Batteries, Wet along with pictures of how toproperly package, block, and brace future loads for shipment. Information was also provided to the operationalmanagers of the terminal in Nassau so they could properly inspect the In-gate of future loads.
